PROJECT 6: RDS + Route53
Date: Day 9
What I built:

Created MySQL RDS database (dipesh-security-db) using Sandbox template
Configured database inside dipesh-security-vpc with private access only
Created new DB subnet group with subnets in multiple availability zones
Enabled automated backups with 7 day retention period
Enabled storage encryption at rest
Enabled deletion protection to prevent accidental database removal
Created private Route53 hosted zone (dipesh.internal) inside dipesh-security-vpc
Created CNAME DNS record pointing to RDS endpoint
Configured Route53 health check and cancelled before creation to avoid charges

Security concepts applied:

Database placed inside custom VPC not default VPC
Public accessibility disabled — database not exposed to internet
New dedicated security group created for database (dipesh-db-sg)
Storage encryption enabled for data at rest protection
Automated backups enabled for disaster recovery
Deletion protection enabled to prevent accidental data loss
Private hosted zone used for internal DNS resolution only
Health check configured but cancelled due to cost awareness

Challenges faced and resolved:

First database creation failed with VPC mismatch error
EC2 security group was in different VPC than RDS
Fixed by creating new dedicated security group during RDS creation
Second attempt failed with same VPC error
Discovered VPC IDs were confusing between dipesh-security-vpc and default VPC
Identified correct VPC by checking VPC ID in console
Third attempt failed due to insufficient subnets
RDS requires subnets in minimum 2 availability zones
Fixed by creating dipesh-private-subnet-2 in us-east-1b with CIDR 10.0.3.0/24
Database created successfully after this fix
Route53 health check cancelled before creation
Discovered health checks are charged per region
8 regions would cost $4 per month minimum
Documented as best practice for production environments

Real world value:

RDS managed database is used by majority of companies on AWS
Private database with no public access is mandatory security requirement
Encryption at rest is required for compliance frameworks like SOC2 and PCI DSS
Automated backups are critical for disaster recovery planning
Route53 private hosted zones allow internal DNS without exposing to internet
Cost awareness during setup prevents unexpected cloud bills

Key learnings:

RDS requires subnets in at least 2 availability zones for subnet group
Always create dedicated security groups for each service
VPC selection must match across all related resources
Public accessibility must always be disabled for databases
Encryption and deletion protection should always be enabled
Route53 health checks have per region costs — plan carefully
Private hosted zones keep DNS resolution internal to VPC
Always check cost implications before creating Route53 resources
